=== Drag <sec:drag>

We use the standard quadratic drag law written in a numerically stable form:

$
F_"drag" (v) = k v abs(v),
quad
k := 1/2 rho_w C_d A
$ <eq:drag>

where $C_d$ is the drag coefficient and $A$ is the effective frontal cross section area.
A representative range is $C_d approx$ 0.9--1.1 and $A approx$ 0.08--0.12 #unit[m^2] @barbosa2018assessment.
This lands $k$ roughly in the range $k approx$ 30--60 #unit[N/(m/s)^2] for typical human freedivers.
In this work, we treat $C_d$ as approximately fixed for a given configuration, while interpreting improvements in streamlining and body position as changes in the effective area $A$, which can be trained and optimized.

