== Re-parameterization and Nondimensionalization <sec:reparam-nondim>

This section re-expresses the vertical dynamics in terms of a small set of physically interpretable and easily measurable parameters.
We assume the explicit suit term has been absorbed into the constant displaced-volume term as described previously, and proceed using $V_"const"$ and the Boyle gas model @eq:boyle.

=== Large-Depth Net Load <sec:large-depth-net-load>

Define the asymptotic (large-depth) net load

$
Delta F_oo := m g - rho_w g V_"const"
$ <eq:DeltaF-oo>

which is the weight minus asymptotic buoyancy.

Interpretation:

- If $Delta F_oo > 0$, the diver is (slightly) negative at great depth; a finite free-fall terminal speed exists.
- If $Delta F_oo = 0$, the diver is neutrally buoyant as $z -> oo$; deep free-fall tends to zero speed.
- If $Delta F_oo < 0$, the diver is positive at great depth; pure free-fall descent is not possible.

=== Neutral Depth $z_n$ <sec:neutral-depth>

Define $z_n$ as the depth where weight equals buoyancy under the depth-compressed gas model:

$
m g = B(z_n) = rho_w g (V_"const" + V_"gas" (z_n))
$ <eq:zn-def>

Equivalently,

$
Delta F_oo = rho_w g V_"gas" (z_n).
$ <eq:zn-DeltaF>

Writing @eq:boyle as $V_"gas" (z) = V_("gas", 0) L_p/(L_p + z)$ yields

$
1 + z_n/L_p = (rho_w g V_("gas", 0)) / (Delta F_oo),
quad "equivalently" quad
z_n = L_p ((rho_w g V_("gas", 0)) / (Delta F_oo) - 1).
$ <eq:zn-link>

This identity shows how the neutral depth couples surface compressible gas volume $V_("gas", 0)$ and deep load $Delta F_oo$.
At fixed $V_("gas", 0)$, adding weight increases $Delta F_oo$ and shifts $z_n$ shallower,
while removing weight decreases $Delta F_oo$ and shifts $z_n$ deeper.
Typical values of $z_n$ for freedivers per AIDA guidance are $approx$ 10--20 #unit[m] for shallower dives @aida3manual and dives as deep as #qty[60][m] @aida4manual.

=== Deep Terminal Velocity <sec:deep-terminal-velocity>

When $Delta F_oo > 0$ and thrust is zero ($F_"mech" (t) = 0$), define the deep terminal speed by balancing deep load with quadratic drag @eq:drag:

$
v_oo := sqrt((Delta F_oo) / k)
$ <eq:v-oo>

Equivalently,

$
Delta F_oo = k v_oo^2,
quad
k = (Delta F_oo) / v_oo^2.
$ <eq:k-from-voo>

The quantity $v_oo$ should be interpreted as the *asymptotic free-fall (glide) speed* that would be approached at sufficiently large depth, where buoyancy has nearly reached its deep limit and the net load approaches $Delta F_oo$.
It is not the average descent speed of a full constant-weight dive, since real dives include an active descent phase above $z_n$, a transition region near $z_n$, and a turn plus active ascent.

Human breath-hold dive profiles are often discussed at characteristic vertical speeds around #qty[1][m/s] in the literature @bosco2007breath @patrician2021breath.
These values are consistent with using $v_oo$ on the order of $v_oo approx$ 0.8--1.2 #unit[m/s] as a practical scale for constant-weight-style glides in a well-weighted diver.

=== Re-parameterized Equation of Motion <sec:eom-reparam>

Define the net load (downward-positive) as $Delta F (z) := m g - B (z)$.
With suit absorbed into $V_"const"$ and Boyle-compressed gas @eq:boyle, we obtain the compact form

$
Delta F (z)
= Delta F_oo (z - z_n)/(L_p + z)
= k v_oo^2 (z - z_n)/(L_p + z),
$ <eq:W-voo>

where $Delta F_oo := m g - rho_w g V_"const"$, $z_n$ is the neutral depth @eq:zn-link,
and $Delta F_oo = k v_oo^2$ by @eq:k-from-voo.

Substituting @eq:W-voo and quadratic drag @eq:drag into the vertical equation of motion @eq:eom gives

$
m dot(v)
= F_"mech" (t)
+ k v_oo^2 (z - z_n)/(L_p + z)
- k v abs(v).
$ <eq:eom-reparam>

Equivalently,

$
m dot(v)
= F_"mech" (t)
+ k [ v_oo^2 (z - z_n)/(L_p + z) - v abs(v) ].
$ <eq:eom-reparam-k>

This representation is governed by three physically interpretable parameters:
the deep load $Delta F_oo$ (equivalently $v_oo$), the neutral depth $z_n$, and the pressure length $L_p$.
All remaining depth dependence enters only through the ratio $(z - z_n)/(L_p + z)$.

=== Nondimensionalization <sec:nondimensionalization>

The re-parameterized equation of motion @eq:eom-reparam-k admits a natural nondimensional form using $v_oo$ and $L_p$ as characteristic scales.
Define the dimensionless variables

$
tilde(z) := z / L_p,
quad
tilde(z)_n := z_n / L_p,
quad
tilde(v) := v / v_oo,
quad
tilde(t) := (v_oo / L_p) t.
$ <eq:nondim-vars>

With these definitions,

$
dot(v) = (v_oo^2 / L_p) (dif tilde(v)) / (dif tilde(t)).
$ <eq:vdot-scale>

Substituting @eq:nondim-vars and @eq:vdot-scale into @eq:eom-reparam-k gives

$
m (v_oo^2 / L_p) (dif tilde(v)) / (dif tilde(t))
=
F_"mech" (t)
+ k v_oo^2 (tilde(z) - tilde(z)_n)/(1 + tilde(z))
- k v_oo^2 tilde(v) abs(tilde(v)).
$

Dividing through by the characteristic force scale $k v_oo^2 = Delta F_oo$ yields the dimensionless equation

$
(m / (k L_p)) (dif tilde(v))/(dif tilde(t))
=
tilde(F)_"mech" (tilde(t))
+ (1 - (1 + tilde(z)_n)/(1 + tilde(z)))
- tilde(v) abs(tilde(v)),
$ <eq:eom-nondim>

where the dimensionless control input is

$
tilde(F)_"mech" (tilde(t)) := (F_"mech" (t)) / (Delta F_oo).
$ <eq:F-tilde>

The single remaining dimensionless inertia parameter is

$
lambda := m / (k L_p),
$ <eq:lambda>

so that the nondimensional form may be written as

$
lambda (dif tilde(v))/(dif tilde(t))
=
tilde(F)_"mech" (tilde(t))
+ (1 - (1 + tilde(z)_n)/(1 + tilde(z)))
- tilde(v) abs(tilde(v)).
$ <eq:eom-nondim-lambda>

In the quasi-steady limit, acceleration is small compared to the dominant force balance between thrust, buoyancy, and drag, and the dynamics reduce to an instantaneous force balance on each segment of motion.

== Physiological Model and Budgets <sec:phys-model-budgets>

=== #O2 and #CO2 <sec:o2-co2>

Following AIDA manual conventions @aida4manual, we model freediving performance through *integrated resource bookkeeping* over a dive as shown in @fig:o2-and-co2-budget.
The attempt terminates when the first limiting factor is reached.
In this exploratory analysis we track two physiological resources: usable #O2 and #CO2 tolerance.

